http://help.autodesk.com/cloudhelp/2019/ENU/FBX-Developer-Help/cpp_ref/class_fbx_surface_lambert.html

Default values were extracted from 2019.5 runtime.
Emissive factor property. This factor is used to attenuate the emissive color.
Ambient factor property. This factor is used to attenuate the ambient color.
Diffuse factor property. This factor is used to attenuate the diffuse color.
NormalMap property. This property can be used to specify the distortion of the surface normals and create the illusion of a bumpy surface.
Bump property. This property is used to distort the surface normal and create the illusion of a bumpy surface.
Bump factor property. This factor is used to make a surface more or less bumpy.
Transparency factor property.  This property is used to make a surface more or less opaque (0 = opaque, 1 = transparent).

http://help.autodesk.com/cloudhelp/2019/ENU/FBX-Developer-Help/cpp_ref/class_fbx_surface_phong.html

Default values were extracted from 2019.5 runtime.
Specular factor property. This factor is used to attenuate the specular color.
Reflection color property. This property is used to implement reflection mapping.
Reflection factor property. This property is used to attenuate the reflection color.

glTF defines materials using a common set of parameters that are based on widely used material representations from Physically-Based Rendering (PBR).
Specifically, glTF uses the metallic-roughness material model.
Using this declarative representation of materials enables a glTF file to be rendered consistently across platforms.
The emissive color of the material. Default: [0,0,0]
The occlusion map indicating areas of indirect lighting.
The emissive map controls the color and intensity of the light being emitted by the material.

The alphaMpde defines how the alpha value of the main factor and texture should be interpreted map indicating areas of indirect lighting.
Can be OPAQUE, MASK or BLEND. Default: "OPAQUE"
The cutoff threshold. This value is only used for alpha mode MASK. Default: 0.5
Specifies whether the material is double sided. Default: false
The base color of the material. Default: [1,1,1,1]
The metalness of the material. Default: 1
The roughness of the material. Default: 1
A single map for metalness and roughness! The metalness values is in the "b" and the roughness in the "g" color channel.

This bundle is modeled after the open standard Autodesk Standard Surface version 1.0.1, see
https://autodesk.github.io/standard-surface/ .
reflection roughness; squared internally before passed to the BSDF to achieve a more uniform roughness look over the parameter range
orientation of anisotropy; range [0,1] (1 means 180 degrees)

the distance travelled inside the material by white light before its color becomes exactly transmission_color by Beer's law, determining the extinction coefficient of the interior medium; if zero, transmission_color acts as a constant (on-surface) transmission tint; range [0,infinity)
scattering coefficient of the interior medium
the anisotropy of the Henyey-Greenstein phase function of the interior medium; range [-1,1]
dispersion Abbe number, describing how much the index of refraction varies across wavelengths
additional (positive or negative) roughness on top of specular_roughness
subsurface color, used by subsurface(...) closure
subsurface radii (i.e. mean free paths) of the red, green, and blue channels
anisotropy of the subsurface medium phase function; range [-1,1]
reflection weight (reflection color is fixed to white)
tint color for the light coming from all layers below
coat reflection roughness; squared internally before passed to the BSDF to achieve a more linear perceptual response [Burley2012]
orientation of anisotropy; range [0,1] (where 1 means 180 degrees)
shading normal for the coating reflections; optional, overrides the default shading normal; has no effect on the closure combination weights
how much to additionally modulate diffuse reflection and subsurface scattering saturation; range [0,1]
how much to affect the roughness of the specular reflection layers below; range [0,1]
if true, the object is considered infinitely thin and the surface double-sided
the (colored) opacity of the surface (fully opaque by default)

(not subject to standard) 
Data is expected to be in [0,1] range with the geometric normal = [0.5, 0.5, 1.0].
The tangent frame is oriented in accordance with OpenGL and Unity.
